### A3: Closed Ecological Life Support Systems (CELSS)

#### A3.1 Fundamental Requirements

**Human Metabolic Needs (Per Person Per Day):**

```
Oxygen Consumption: 0.84 kg O₂/day
CO₂ Production: 1.0 kg CO₂/day
Water Consumption:
  - Drinking: 2.0 kg
  - Food preparation: 1.5 kg
  - Hygiene: 5.0 kg
  - Total: 8.5 kg/day (with 98% recycling: 0.17 kg makeup/day)
  
Food Requirement: 0.6 kg dry mass/day (2,500 kcal)
Waste Production:
  - Urine: 1.5 kg/day
  - Feces: 0.15 kg/day
  - Perspiration/respiration: 2.0 kg/day
  - Total metabolic waste: 3.65 kg/day
```

**Closure Definitions:**

```
Closure Rate = (Mass Recycled) / (Mass Required) × 100%

Current ISS Performance (2024 data):
  - Oxygen: 75% (water electrolysis from recycled water)
  - Water: 93% (urine processor + humidity condenser)
  - Food: 0% (all resupply from Earth)
  
Target for Mars Mission (2045):
  - Oxygen: 98%
  - Water: 98%
  - Food: 80% (supplement vitamins, complex proteins)
  
Target for Permanent Settlement (2060):
  - Oxygen: 99.5%
  - Water: 99%
  - Food: 95%
```

#### A3.2 Atmosphere Revitalization Systems

**Current Technology (ISS ECLSS):**

```
CO₂ Removal: 
  - Primary: 4-Bed Molecular Sieve (4BMS)
    - Process: Zeolite adsorption
    - Regeneration: Vacuum exposure
    - Efficiency: 99% removal
    - Power: 1.2 kW
    
  - Backup: Carbon Dioxide Removal Assembly (CDRA)
    - Similar function, different design
    - Redundancy for safety

CO₂ Reduction:
  - Sabatier Reactor: CO₂ + 4H₂ → CH₄ + 2H₂O
    - Recovers 50% of oxygen mass (via water electrolysis)
    - Vents methane (lost)
    - Power: 0.6 kW
    
  - Bosch Reactor (alternative): CO₂ + 2H₂ → C + 2H₂O
    - Recovers 100% of oxygen mass
    - Produces solid carbon (easier to handle than methane)
    - Higher temperature: 600-700°C
    - TRL: 6 (demonstrated but not deployed)
    - Power: 3 kW
    - Preferred for long-duration missions

Oxygen Generation:
  - OGS (Oxygen Generation System): 2H₂O → 2H₂ + O₂
    - PEM electrolysis
    - Rate: 2.3-9 kg O₂/day (ISS crew of 3-7)
    - Power: 1 kW per kg O₂/day
    - Efficiency: 75% (electrical)
```

**Advanced Biological System (MELiSSA Concept):**

```
Micro-Ecological Life Support System Alternative (European Space Agency)

4-Compartment Design:

Compartment I: Thermophilic Anaerobic Digestion
  - Input: Solid waste (feces, food waste, inedible biomass)
  - Bacteria: Thermophiles at 55°C
  - Output: VFAs (volatile fatty acids), NH₄, CO₂, minerals
  - Function: Liquefaction and mineralization
  
Compartment II: Photoheterotrophic Bacteria
  - Input: VFAs from Compartment I
  - Bacteria: Rhodospirillum rubrum
  - Output: CO₂, NH₄, minerals
  - Function: Further breakdown to simple molecules
  
Compartment III: Nitrifying Bacteria
  - Input: NH₄ (ammonia)
  - Bacteria: Nitrosomonas, Nitrobacter
  - Output: NO₃ (nitrate - plant fertilizer)
  - Function: Convert ammonia to usable nitrogen
  
Compartment IV: Photosynthesis (Algae + Higher Plants)
  - Input: CO₂, NO₃, minerals, light
  - Organisms: Spirulina (algae) + lettuce, tomatoes, wheat (higher plants)
  - Output: O₂, edible biomass, H₂O (transpiration)
  - Function: Oxygen production, food, water recycling

Closure Performance:
  - Oxygen: 95-100% (photosynthesis exceeds need)
  - Water: 98% (plant transpiration)
  - Food: 60-70% (caloric basis)
  - Waste: 100% recycled to nutrients

Challenges:
  - Stability: Microbial balance sensitive to perturbations
  - Volume: Requires 100-150 m³ per person
  - Power: 4-6 kW per person (LED lighting)
  - Control: Complex monitoring and adjustment
  
Status: TRL 5-6 (key components validated in ground tests)
Target: Operational for Mars transit by 2040
```

#### A3.3 Water Recovery Systems

**ISS Water Recovery System:**

```
Components:

1. Urine Processor Assembly (UPA):
   - Process: Vacuum distillation
   - Temperature: 130°C (under vacuum)
   - Pretreatment: Chemical stabilization (prevent precipitation)
   - Output: ~85% pure water (contains volatiles)
   - Brine disposal: 15% waste (concentrated salts and organics)
   - Power: 2.5 kW
   - Recovery rate: 70-75% (limited by brine management)

2. Water Processor Assembly (WPA):
   - Input: Distillate from UPA + humidity condensate
   - Process:
     a. Catalytic oxidation (650°C): Destroys organics
     b. Ion exchange: Removes dissolved ions
     c. Filtration: Particulate removal
   - Output: Potable water (meets EPA standards)
   - Recovery: 98% from humidity; 85% from urine (combined: 93%)
   - Power: 0.8 kW

Improvement Pathways (2030-2040):

Forward Osmosis (FO):
  - Process: Osmotic pressure drives water through membrane
  - Advantage: No high temperature; lower power
  - Recovery potential: 90% from urine
  - Power: 0.5 kW
  - TRL: 5-6 for space application
  
Supercritical Water Oxidation (SCWO):
  - Process: Water at 400°C, 250 bar oxidizes all organics
  - Output: Pure water + CO₂ + salts
  - Advantage: Handles any waste stream
  - Recovery: 95%+
  - Power: 3 kW (energy partially recovered)
  - TRL: 4-5 (demonstrated terrestrially)
  - Challenge: High-pressure containment; corrosion
```

**Biological Water Recovery (Plant Transpiration):**

```
Process: Plants absorb water → photosynthesis → transpiration → condensation

Efficiency: 98-99% (almost all water taken up is released)
Purity: Distilled-water quality (no contaminants transpired)
Byproducts: Oxygen production (beneficial)

System Design:
  - Plant growth area: 50 m² per person
  - Water throughput: 5 kg/day per person
  - Transpiration recovery: 4.9 kg/day
  - Makeup water: 0.1 kg/day

Integration with Food Production:
  - Dual-purpose: Water recycling AND food production
  - Mass efficiency: Single system serves two functions
  - Power: Lighting for photosynthesis (3-4 kW per person)
  
Challenge: Requires significant volume and continuous maintenance
```

#### A3.4 Food Production Systems

**Controlled Environment Agriculture (CEA) for Space:**

```
Requirements per Person:
  - Caloric need: 2,500 kcal/day
  - Protein: 70g/day
  - Vitamins, minerals: Varied (micronutrients)
  
Crop Selection Criteria:
  - High caloric yield per area
  - Short growth cycle
  - Low inedible biomass
  - Complete nutrition profile (or complementary crops)
  - Tolerance to controlled environment
```

**Candidate Crops (Ranked by Space Suitability):**

| Crop | Yield (kcal/m²/day) | Protein (%) | Growth Time (days) | Edible Fraction | Notes |
|------|---------------------|-------------|-------------------|-----------------|-------|
| **Sweet Potato** | 45 | 4% | 90-120 | 85% | Highest caloric density; vitamin A |
| **Potato** | 40 | 8% | 70-90 | 80% | Excellent yield; familiar |
| **Rice** | 35 | 8% | 90-120 | 90% | Staple grain; high yield |
| **Soybean** | 28 | 36% | 90-120 | 90% | Complete protein; versatile |
| **Wheat** | 32 | 13% | 90-120 | 90% | Grain staple; breadmaking |
| **Quinoa** | 30 | 14% | 90-120 | 95% | Complete protein; resilient |
| **Lettuce** | 3 | 5% | 30-45 | 100% | Vitamin K, C; low calorie |
| **Tomato** | 5 | 4% | 60-90 | 95% | Vitamins C, K; flavor diversity |
| **Spirulina (algae)** | 50 | 60% | Continuous | 100% | Highest protein; requires liquid culture |

**Recommended Crop Mix (Nutritionally Complete):**

```
Primary Calories (60% of diet):
  - Sweet potato: 25 m²
  - Rice: 15 m²
  
Protein (25% of diet):
  - Soybean: 10 m²
  - Spirulina: 5 m² (tank culture)
  
Micronutrients & Variety (15% of diet):
  - Lettuce, tomato, herbs: 5 m²
  
Total Growing Area: 60 m² per person (conservatively)
With vertical stacking (×3 levels): 20 m² footprint per person
```

**Growth System Design:**

```
Hydroponics vs. Aeroponics vs. Aquaponics:

Hydroponics (Selected for Mars/Moon):
  - Nutrient solution circulates past roots
  - Water use: 10% of soil agriculture
  - Advantage: Proven; controllable; simple
  - Disadvantage: Requires nutrient resupply (initially)
  
Aeroponics:
  - Roots suspended; misted with nutrients
  - Water use: 5% of soil agriculture
  - Advantage: Maximum oxygenation of roots; faster growth
  - Disadvantage: Clogging of misters; complexity
  
Aquaponics:
  - Fish waste provides nutrients for plants
  - Plants filter water for fish
  - Advantage: Protein source (fish); closed loop
  - Disadvantage: Complexity; fish care requirements

Environmental Control:
  - Atmosphere: 400 ppm CO₂ (enriched for faster growth)
  - Temperature: 20-25°C
  - Humidity: 60-70%
  - Light: LED arrays (red 660nm + blue 450nm)
    - Intensity: 400-600 μmol/m²/s (PPFD)
    - Photoperiod: 16 hours/day
    - Power: 50-70 W/m² of growing area
  
For 60 m² per person:
  - Lighting power: 3-4 kW
  - Climate control: 0.5 kW
  - Pumps & monitoring: 0.3 kW
  - Total: 4-5 kW per person (continuous)
```

**Mass Balance for Food Production:**

```
Inputs (per person per year):
  - Water: 2,000 kg (with 98% recycling)
  - CO₂: 365 kg (from human respiration—perfectly matched!)
  - Minerals (NPK + micronutrients): 15 kg (initial; recycled from waste)
  - Seeds: 2 kg
  
Outputs:
  - Food biomass (edible): 220 kg (dry mass)
  - Oxygen: 300 kg (exceeds human need of 307 kg—nearly balanced!)
  - Inedible biomass: 50 kg (recycled to nutrient solution)
  
Net Resource Need:
  - Makeup water: ~40 kg/year
  - Mineral supplements: ~3 kg/year (losses in processing)
  - Seeds: 2 kg/year
  
Closure Achievement: 95% for oxygen, 98% for water, 80% for food (remaining 20% from supplements)
```

#### A3.5 Integrated CELSS Architecture for Mars Habitat

**4-Person Mars Base (Self-Sufficient Design):**

```
Module 1: Habitation & Command (100 m³)
  - Living quarters, workstations, medical
  - Crew: 4 people
  
Module 2: Life Support (120 m³)
  - Water recycling: UPA, WPA, forward osmosis
  - Atmosphere: CO₂ removal, Bosch reactor, O₂ generation
  - Waste processing: SCWO unit
  - Power: 8 kW dedicated
  - Mass: 12 tons (equipment)
  
Module 3: Plant Growth Chamber (200 m³)
  - Growing area: 240 m² (60 m² per person)
  - 3 vertical levels
  - LED lighting: 16 kW
  - Climate control: 2 kW
  - Mass: 20 tons (structure, lights, hydroponics)
  
Module 4: Workshop & Storage (80 m³)
  - Spare parts, tools, emergency supplies
  - 6-month food reserve (emergency)
  
Module 5: Airlock & EVA Prep (40 m³)
  - Suits, tools, decontamination
  
Total Pressurized Volume: 540 m³ (135 m³ per person)
Total Mass (equipment): 45 tons
Power Requirement: 28 kW continuous
  - Life support: 8 kW
  - Plant growth: 18 kW
  - Hab systems: 2 kW

Energy Source:
  - Nuclear reactor: 50 kW thermal → 15 kW electric (Kilopower-class)
  - Solar array: 100 kW peak → 20 kW average (backup, peaks)
  - Total: 35 kW available; 28 kW required (20% margin)
```

**Closure Performance (After 5 Years Operation):**

| Resource | Closure % | Makeup Required (kg/year) | Source |
|----------|-----------|---------------------------|--------|
| Oxygen | 99.8% | 6 kg/person | Electrolysis from makeup water |
| Water | 99% | 80 kg/person | Atmospheric extraction (Mars ISRU) |
| Food (calories) | 85% | 30 kg/person | Supplement shipments |
| Vitamins/Minerals | 60% | 10 kg/person | Resupply |
| Nitrogen (buffer gas) | 98% | 5 kg/person | Atmospheric extraction |

**Total Annual Resupply Need: 130 kg/person = 520 kg for 4-person base**

Compare to ISS: ~6,000 kg/person/year (46× reduction)
Compare to Antarctic station: ~2,000 kg/person/year (15× reduction)

**Conclusion:** Mars base achieves near-autonomy. 520 kg/year resupply is manageable with 1 cargo mission every 26 months (launch window).

