## APPENDIX C: GOVERNANCE & LEGAL FRAMEWORKS

### C1: International Space Resource Authority (ISRA)—Phased Implementation

#### C1.1 Phase 1: Voluntary Registry (2025-2032)

**Establishment:**

```
Host Organization: United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs (UNOOSA)
Legal Basis: COPUOS resolution (non-binding)
Budget: $10M/year (funded by voluntary contributions)
Staff: 20 personnel (Vienna HQ)

Functions:
  1. Voluntary registration of space resource claims
  2. Public database of intended activities
  3. Conflict notification (but no arbitration power)
  4. Annual reporting on space resource activities
  5. Best practices development (non-binding)
```

**Registry Process:**

```
Registration Tiers:

Tier 1: Notification of Intent
  - Entity declares interest in specific celestial body region
  - Non-exclusive; informational only
  - Fee: $5,000 per notification
  - Term: 2 years, renewable
  - Requirement: None (open to all)
  
Tier 2: Prospecting Declaration
  - Entity commits to prospecting mission
  - Non-exclusive; multiple entities can prospect same area
  - Fee: $50,000 per declaration
  - Term: 5 years
  - Requirement: Demonstrate financial and technical capability ($50M in funding)
  
Tier 3: Extraction Intention
  - Entity declares intent to extract resources from specific site
  - Exclusive flag: Alerts other entities of planned exclusive use
  - Fee: $500,000
  - Term: 10 years, renewable
  - Requirement: Demonstrated prospecting results; $500M in funding

Data Transparency:
  - All Tier 1-3 registrations publicly searchable
  - Entities encouraged (not required) to share prospecting data
  - Conflict notification: ISRA alerts entities of overlapping claims
```

**Outcomes (2025-2032):**

```
Expected Registrations:
  - Tier 1: 200-300 (many speculative)
  - Tier 2: 30-50 (serious prospectors)
  - Tier 3: 5-10 (funded extraction missions)
  
Precedent Building:
  - Norms established for claim registration
  - Database of celestial body features and claims
  - Working relationships between space agencies/companies
  - Foundation for binding regime in Phase 2
  
Revenue: ~$10-15M/year (self-funding achieved by Year 5)
```

#### C1.2 Phase 2: Licensing Regime (2032-2045)

**Treaty Basis:**

```
Instrument: "Revised Artemis Accords Framework" or "Moon-Mars Resources Treaty"
Negotiation: 2028-2031 (parallel to Phase 1 operation)
Ratification: 2032 (requires 20 nations for entry into force)
Legal Character: Binding international agreement

Core Provisions:
  1. Resource extraction rights defined (extraction ≠ sovereignty)
  2. ISRA empowered to issue exclusive licenses
  3. Royalty mechanism established
  4. Benefit-sharing fund created
  5. Dispute arbitration mandatory
  6. Environmental protection standards
```

**Licensing Authority:**

```
Governing Council:
  - 25 member states (rotating 3-year terms)
  - 5 permanent seats: USA, Russia, China, EU (collective), India
  - Decisions: 2/3 majority for licenses; consensus for major policy
  
Technical Committee:
  - 15 independent experts (geologists, engineers, lawyers, ethicists)
  - 5-year terms, renewable once
  - Reviews license applications; advises Council
  
Secretariat:
  - Executive Director (appointed by Council)
  - 150 staff (legal, technical, financial, compliance)
  - Budget: $100M/year
```

**License Types:**

```
Type A: Prospecting License
  - Duration: 5 years, renewable once
  - Exclusivity: Non-exclusive (multiple licensees per area)
  - Area: Up to 1,000 km² (lunar); 10,000 km² (Mars); individual asteroids
  - Fee: $100,000 application + $10,000/year
  - Requirement: 
    * Technical plan
    * Financial capability ($100M minimum)
    * Environmental impact assessment
    * Safety protocols
  - Obligation: Annual reporting; data sharing after 3-year proprietary period
  
Type B: Exploration License
  - Duration: 10 years, renewable
  - Exclusivity: Exclusive for area (no overlapping licenses)
  - Area: Up to 100 km² (lunar/Mars); 1 asteroid (full exclusive rights)
  - Fee: $500,000 application + $50,000/km²/year
  - Requirement:
    * Successful prospecting (Type A prerequisite)
    * Detailed extraction plan
    * Financial capability ($1B minimum)
    * Environmental management plan
    * Benefit-sharing proposal
  - Obligation: Commence operations within 5 years or forfeit
  
Type C: Extraction License
  - Duration: 20 years, renewable indefinitely (if compliant)
  - Exclusivity: Full exclusive extraction rights
  - Area: Up to 50 km² (lunar/Mars); 1 asteroid
  - Fee: $2M application + 2% ad valorem royalty on gross extraction value
  - Requirement:
    * Successful exploration (Type B prerequisite)
    * Operational facility design approved
    * Financial capability ($5B minimum for large operations)
    * Comprehensive environmental monitoring
    * Decommissioning plan and bond
  - Obligation: Quarterly production reports; annual safety audits; royalty payments
```

**Royalty Structure:**

```
Calculation:
  Gross Value = (Mass Extracted) × (Benchmark Price)
  
Benchmark Prices (Updated Annually):
  - Water ice: $1,000/kg (propellant value equivalent)
  - Oxygen: $500/kg
  - Metals (common): $5/kg (in-space utilization value)
  - PGMs: $30,000/kg (Earth market price)
  - Rare earth elements: Variable by element
  
Royalty Rate: 2% of gross value (base)
  - Reduced to 1% for first 5 years (incentive for early movers)
  - Increased to 3% if profits exceed 30% IRR (windfall provision)
  
Payment: Quarterly, in USD or kind (resources delivered to ISRA trust)

Example:
  Lunar water extraction: 1,000 tons/year
  Gross value: 1M kg × $1,000/kg = $1B/year
  Royalty: 2% × $1B = $20M/year
```

**Benefit-Sharing Fund:**

```
Revenue Sources:
  - Royalties: $20-100M/year (by 2040)
  - License fees: $10-20M/year
  - Fines for non-compliance: $5-10M/year
  - Total: $35-130M/year

Fund Allocation (Annual):
- 40% → Space capacity building for developing nations
    * Satellite technology transfer
    * Scholarships for space science students
    * Co-investment in developing nations' space missions
    
  - 30% → Terrestrial sustainable development
    * Clean water projects using space life-support tech
    * Renewable energy in remote areas
    * Climate adaptation (especially vulnerable nations)
    
  - 20% → Scientific research (open-access)
    * Planetary science grants
    * Astrobiology research
    * Space medicine
    
  - 10% → ISRA operations
    * Administrative costs
    * Compliance monitoring
    * Enforcement
    
Governance: Independent board (majority from developing nations); annual public audit
```

#### C1.3 Phase 3: Full Regulatory Authority (2045+)

**Expanded Functions:**

```
1. Environmental Protection:
   - Planetary Protection Officer (full-time)
   - Forward/backward contamination protocols
   - Heritage site designation (e.g., Apollo landing sites)
   - Ecosystem monitoring (if life discovered)
   
2. Safety Certification:
   - Approve life support systems for human missions
   - Radiation protection standards
   - Emergency response requirements
   - Accident investigation authority
   
3. Traffic Management:
   - Coordinate with existing space traffic systems
   - Lunar/Mars orbit management
   - Surface landing zone allocation
   - Collision avoidance protocols
   
4. Conflict Resolution:
   - Binding arbitration for disputes
   - Enforcement mechanisms (fines, license suspension)
   - Appeals process (3-judge panel)
```

**Revenue Scaling:**

```
By 2050:
  - Active licenses: 100-200 (50 extraction, 150 exploration/prospecting)
  - Annual royalties: $500M-2B (from mature SBSP, asteroid mining, lunar propellant)
  - Budget: $200M/year (self-funded)
  - Staff: 400 (includes inspectors, scientists, legal team)
  
Budget Allocation:
  - Operations (licensing, arbitration): 30%
  - Compliance & inspection: 25%
  - Scientific research grants: 20%
  - Developing nation capacity building: 15%
  - Emergency fund (disaster response): 10%
```

---

### C2: Multiplanetary Alliance Treaty—Practical Cooperation Framework

#### C2.1 Treaty Structure

**Preamble:**

```
Recognizing:
  - The common interest of all humanity in space exploration
  - The need for cooperation to ensure safety and sustainability
  - The benefits of shared infrastructure and open science
  - The imperative to extend rule of law beyond Earth

The States Parties Agree to establish the Multiplanetary Alliance for:
  - Shared infrastructure development
  - Mutual assistance in emergencies
  - Open scientific collaboration
  - Equitable distribution of benefits
```

**Membership:**

```
Eligibility:
  - Any sovereign state or recognized space agency
  - Corporations/entities as "Observer Members" (no voting rights)
  
Obligations:
  - Financial contribution (GDP-weighted, minimum $10M/year)
  - Commitment to mutual assistance
  - Transparency in space resource activities
  - Compliance with safety standards
  
Rights:
  - Access to shared infrastructure (at cost)
  - Participation in governance
  - Access to open science database
  - Dispute resolution services
```

#### C2.2 Common Infrastructure Fund

**Purpose:**

```
Fund essential shared infrastructure that no single entity would build:
  - Cislunar communication network
  - Lunar positioning system (GPS equivalent)
  - Mars orbital relay satellites
  - Emergency rescue capability
  - Standardized docking interfaces
```

**Funding Model:**

```
Capitalization (2025-2035): $5B
  - 60% from member states (GDP-weighted)
  - 30% from private companies (in exchange for usage rights)
  - 10% from philanthropic sources
  
Annual Operating Budget (by 2040): $500M
  - Membership fees: $300M
  - Usage fees (commercial): $150M
  - Investment returns: $50M
  
Fund Management:
  - Independent board (7 members: 3 government, 2 private, 2 at-large)
  - Transparent accounting (annual public report)
  - Procurement via competitive bidding
```

**Priority Projects (2030-2045):**

```
1. Lunar Communications Network ($1.2B)
   - 4 relay satellites in lunar orbit
   - Ground stations at poles
   - Coverage: 95% of lunar surface
   - Bandwidth: 100 Mbps per user
   - Completion: 2032

2. Lunar Positioning System ($800M)
   - Constellation of 8 satellites
   - Accuracy: 1 meter (lunar surface)
   - Coverage: 100% of surface
   - Completion: 2034

3. Mars Orbital Communication Relay ($1.5B)
   - 6 satellites in areosynchronous orbit
   - Earth-Mars link: 10 Mbps (at closest approach)
   - Surface coverage: 98%
   - Completion: 2043

4. Cislunar Emergency Response Capability ($1.0B)
   - Rescue vehicle stationed at L1
   - Crew: 2 (rotational)
   - Δv capacity: 5 km/s (reach anywhere in cislunar space)
   - Completion: 2036

5. Standardization Program ($500M)
   - Docking interfaces (ISO standard development)
   - Life support connections
   - Power interfaces
   - Communication protocols
   - Completion: Ongoing
```

#### C2.3 Open Science Pledge

**Principles:**

```
1. Foundational Knowledge is Public Good:
   - Life support research: Fully open, immediate publication
   - Planetary science data: Open within 6 months of collection
   - Human health in space: Open within 1 year (patient privacy protected)
   
2. Applied Technology is Protected (with limits):
   - Commercial processes: 3-year proprietary period
   - After 3 years: Licensing at fair, reasonable, and non-discriminatory (FRAND) terms
   - Safety-critical technology: 1-year proprietary period (faster dissemination)
   
3. Defensive Publication:
   - Entities can publish to prevent patent blocking
   - Encourages innovation over litigation
```

**Open Science Database:**

```
Host: International Academy of Space Sciences (proposed)
Access: Free for academic/research; tiered pricing for commercial

Data Categories:
  - Celestial body composition (regolith samples, spectroscopy)
  - Environmental conditions (radiation maps, temperature profiles)
  - Life support performance (closure rates, failure modes)
  - Propulsion test data (specific impulse, efficiency)
  - Medical data (radiation exposure, bone density loss, anonymized)
  
Contribution Requirements:
  - All Alliance members contribute data from publicly funded missions
  - Private entities encouraged to contribute (via tax incentives)
  - Data format standardized (interoperability)
  
Data Volume Projection (by 2040):
  - 50 TB of planetary science data
  - 10,000 peer-reviewed papers
  - 5,000 engineering reports
  - 1,000 medical case studies
```

**Technology Transfer Mechanism:**

```
For Developing Nations:
  - Free access to all open database content
  - Licensing of proprietary tech at 50% discount (subsidized by fund)
  - Training programs (1,000 scholarships/year by 2040)
  - Co-investment in domestic space programs (matching grants)
  
Intellectual Property:
  - Patents arising from Alliance-funded research: Joint ownership
  - Commercial exploitation: Royalties shared (50% to Alliance fund, 50% to developer)
  - Compulsory licensing in emergencies (e.g., life-threatening situation requires proprietary tech)
```

#### C2.4 Mutual Assistance Compact

**Emergency Response Obligations:**

```
Definition of Emergency:
  - Life-threatening situation (crew injury, life support failure)
  - Imminent catastrophic failure (collision warning, power loss)
  - Loss of communication with mission control
  
Response Requirements:
  Level 1 (Information Sharing): Immediate
    - All members share tracking data, technical expertise
    - No cost; reciprocal obligation
    
  Level 2 (Resource Provision): Within 24 hours
    - Provide spare parts, consumables if available
    - Cost: At-cost reimbursement (no profit)
    
  Level 3 (Active Rescue): Within 72 hours (if capable)
    - Dispatch rescue mission if within Δv capability
    - Cost: Shared among Alliance members (emergency fund)
    
  Level 4 (Evacuation): As needed
    - Accept evacuated crew from distressed mission
    - Provide medical care, temporary accommodation
    - Cost: Alliance emergency fund
```

**Emergency Fund:**

```
Capitalization: $1B (established 2030)
  - Contributions: $100M/year from members (GDP-weighted)
  - Insurance: $50M/year from mission insurance pool
  
Disbursement:
  - Rescue operations: Up to $500M per incident
  - Medical care: Up to $50M per person
  - Salvage operations: Up to $200M per mission
  
Replenishment:
  - Fund replenished to $1B annually
  - Unused funds invested (conservative portfolio)
```

**Precedent Cases (Terrestrial Analogy):**

```
International Maritime Rescue:
  - Ships obligated to rescue distressed vessels
  - Cost-sharing via flag states
  - 200+ years of successful operation
  
Antarctic Treaty Search & Rescue:
  - Multi-nation coordination for station emergencies
  - Shared logistics (aircraft, icebreakers)
  - Zero incidents unresolved
  
Space Precedent:
  - ISS: Multi-nation crew rescue protocols (Soyuz, Crew Dragon backups)
  - Tiangong: Offer to assist ISS in emergencies (2023)
```

#### C2.5 Equitable Benefit Mechanism

**Rationale:**

```
Space resources are "common heritage of humanity" (Outer Space Treaty, Article I)
  - Exploitation permissible, but benefits must flow to all
  - Mechanism balances commercial incentive with equity
  
Design Principles:
  - Modest burden (doesn't kill commercial viability)
  - Transparent allocation
  - Measurable impact
  - Automatic (no bureaucratic delays)
```

**Benefit Flow Structure:**

```
Source: 15% of net profits from space resource extraction
  - Net profit = Revenue - (Operating costs + capital amortization)
  - Calculation: Audited annually by independent accounting firm
  - Payment: Within 90 days of fiscal year end
  
Example:
  Asteroid mining operation
  - Revenue: $600M/year
  - OpEx: $200M/year
  - CapEx amortization: $100M/year
  - Net profit: $300M/year
  - Contribution: 15% × $300M = $45M/year

Threshold: Only applies to operations with net profit > $50M/year
  - Protects early-stage/marginal operations
  - Ensures fund comes from successful ventures
```

**Allocation of Benefit Fund:**

```
Total Fund (projected 2050): $500M-1B/year

Distribution:
  40% → Developing Nations' Space Programs
    - Grants for satellite development
    - Launch vouchers (free access to orbital launch)
    - Co-investment in space startups (50/50 matching)
    - Target: 20 developing nations with operational space programs by 2050
    
  30% → Terrestrial Sustainable Development (UN SDGs)
    - Clean water: Space life-support tech → arid regions
    - Renewable energy: SBSP demonstrations for remote communities
    - Climate adaptation: Early warning systems (satellite-based)
    - Administered via existing UN Development Programme
    
  20% → Global Science Commons
    - Funding for international research collaborations
    - Space telescopes for open-access astronomy
    - Planetary defense (asteroid detection/deflection)
    - Administered via new "Multiplanetary Science Foundation"
    
  10% → Administration & Reserve
    - Alliance operations
    - Emergency contingency
    - Audit and compliance
```

**Accountability:**

```
Oversight Board:
  - 9 members: 6 from developing nations, 2 from developed nations, 1 independent chair
  - 3-year terms, staggered
  - Powers: Approve grants, audit recipients, publish annual report
  
Transparency:
  - All grants >$1M published online
  - Recipient progress reports (annual)
  - Independent evaluation every 5 years
  - Public comment period before major allocations
  
Recourse:
  - Misuse of funds → grant clawback
  - Ineffective programs → reallocation to better alternatives
  - Whistleblower protection for fraud reporting
```

---

### C3: Model Dispute Resolution Procedures

**Arbitration Framework:**

```
Jurisdiction: Space Arbitration Tribunal (SAT)
  - Established under Multiplanetary Alliance Treaty
  - Seat: The Hague, Netherlands (co-located with International Court of Justice)
  - Basis: Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA) Optional Rules for Outer Space

Composition:
  - Panel of 15 permanent arbitrators (experts in space law, engineering, IP)
  - Cases heard by 3-arbitrator panels
  - Parties select 1 arbitrator each; 3rd selected by agreement or SAT appointment
  
Applicable Law:
  - Primary: Multiplanetary Alliance Treaty
  - Secondary: ISRA regulations
  - Tertiary: Outer Space Treaty and customary international law
  - Gap-filling: General principles of law, equity
```

**Dispute Categories:**

```
Type A: Resource Claim Conflicts
  - Example: Two entities claim overlapping extraction rights
  - Timeline: Expedited (90-day decision)
  - Remedy: Boundary clarification, license modification, compensation
  
Type B: Contract Disputes
  - Example: Failure to deliver purchased propellant; facility construction delays
  - Timeline: Standard (180-day decision)
  - Remedy: Damages, specific performance, contract reformation
  
Type C: Environmental Harm
  - Example: Contamination of scientific site; excessive debris generation
  - Timeline: Urgent (45-day preliminary injunction; 120-day final decision)
  - Remedy: Injunction, cleanup order, fines, license suspension
  
Type D: Safety Violations
  - Example: Reckless operation endangering other missions
  - Timeline: Emergency (7-day injunction; 60-day final decision)
  - Remedy: Cease operations, safety upgrades, criminal referral (if egregious)
```

**Procedure:**

```
Step 1: Negotiation (Mandatory, 30 days)
  - Parties must attempt good-faith resolution
  - Mediation available (Alliance-provided mediator)
  - 70% of disputes resolve here
  
Step 2: Arbitration Filing
  - Claimant files notice with SAT ($50,000 fee)
  - Statement of claim (facts, legal basis, remedy sought)
  - Supporting evidence
  
Step 3: Response (30 days)
  - Respondent files answer
  - Counterclaims permitted
  
Step 4: Arbitrator Selection (14 days)
  - Each party selects arbitrator
  - Chair selected
  
Step 5: Evidence Phase (60 days)
  - Document production
  - Technical expert testimony
  - Site inspections (if relevant)
  
Step 6: Hearing (5 days)
  - Oral arguments
  - Witness examination
  - Technical demonstrations
  
Step 7: Decision (30 days after hearing)
  - Written award with reasoning
  - Remedies specified
  - Costs allocated (loser pays 60-80% of costs)
  
Step 8: Enforcement
  - Award binding; enforceable in all Alliance member states
  - Non-compliance → sanctions (license suspension, fines, expulsion from Alliance)
```

**Precedent & Appeals:**

```
Precedent:
  - SAT decisions published (parties can request confidentiality for trade secrets)
  - Create body of space law jurisprudence
  - Non-binding but persuasive for future panels
  
Appeals:
  - Limited: Only for procedural irregularity or manifest error of law
  - Appeal panel: 5 arbitrators (different from original panel)
  - Timeline: 60 days
  - Standard of review: High deference to original panel
```

**Case Study (Hypothetical):**

```
Case: Luna Mining Corp. v. Artemis Propellants LLC

Facts:
  - Both entities hold licenses for adjacent lunar areas (Shackleton Crater)
  - Luna Mining extracts water ice; pipes run near Artemis boundary
  - Artemis alleges: Luna's excavation undermines Artemis's ice deposits (subsurface flow)
  - Luna alleges: Artemis is delaying operations to free-ride on Luna's infrastructure
  
Claims:
  - Artemis seeks: Injunction against Luna's excavation; $50M damages for lost ice
  - Luna seeks: Dismissal; $20M damages for defamation (public allegations harmed stock price)
  
Arbitration:
  - Filed: March 1, 2043
  - Technical expert (hydrogeologist) appointed to assess subsurface ice flow
  - Finding: Minimal flow (5% of Artemis's ice at risk)
  - Hearing: May 15-20, 2043
  
Award (July 1, 2043):
  - Luna's excavation may continue BUT must install barrier at depth of 10 meters
  - Artemis awarded $3M (lost ice value, discounted for speculative nature)
  - Luna's defamation claim dismissed (Artemis's allegations were good-faith)
  - Costs: Luna pays 60% ($800k); Artemis pays 40% ($530k)
  
Outcome:
  - Both parties comply
  - Luna installs barrier ($5M cost)
  - Artemis begins operations (6 months later)
  - Relationship improves; parties negotiate joint logistics agreement
  
Precedent Established:
  - "Subsurface resource flow" doctrine: Licensee responsible for preventing material harm to adjacent licensees
  - Standard: "Material harm" = >10% resource loss
  - Remedy: Technical mitigation preferred over monetary damages (preserves resource use)
```

---

## APPENDIX D: GLOSSARY & ACRONYMS

**Technical Terms:**

```
Aeroponic Agriculture: Growing plants in air/mist without soil or continuous water submersion
Artemis Accords: Non-binding agreements among spacefaring nations (2020) on lunar cooperation principles
Closed Ecological Life Support System (CELSS): Fully recycling life support with biological components
Cryogenic: Extremely low temperature storage (e.g., liquid hydrogen at -253°C)
Delta-v (Δv): Change in velocity; measure of propulsion capability required for orbital maneuvers
Geostationary Earth Orbit (GEO): 35,786 km altitude; satellite orbits Earth in 24 hours (appears stationary)
Halo Orbit: Three-dimensional orbit around a Lagrange point (not a simple circular orbit)
In-Situ Resource Utilization (ISRU): Using materials found on celestial bodies rather than transporting from Earth
Ion Drive: Electric propulsion using ionized gas; high efficiency, low thrust
Lagrange Point (L1, L2, etc.): Points in space where gravitational forces balance; stable locations for spacecraft
Levelized Cost of Energy (LCOE): Total cost of building and operating a power plant per unit of energy produced
Low Earth Orbit (LEO): 200-2,000 km altitude; most satellites and ISS operate here
Near Rectilinear Halo Orbit (NRHO): Specific halo orbit around the Moon; stable, good Earth communication
Net Present Value (NPV): Sum of future cash flows discounted to present value; measures investment profitability
Outer Space Treaty (1967): Foundational international space law; prohibits national appropriation, mandates peaceful use
Permanently Shadowed Region (PSR): Areas (e.g., lunar polar craters) never receiving sunlight; contain water ice
Phased Array Antenna: Antenna with multiple elements whose signals can be combined to steer beam electronically
Platinum Group Metals (PGMs): Platinum, palladium, rhodium, iridium, osmium, ruthenium; rare, high-value metals
Rectenna: Antenna that receives and converts microwave energy to electrical current
Regolith: Loose soil/rock layer on celestial bodies (lunar dust, Martian soil)
Sabatier Reaction: CO₂ + 4H₂ → CH₄ + 2H₂O; used for Mars propellant production
Specific Impulse (Isp): Measure of rocket engine efficiency; higher is better (seconds)
Technology Readiness Level (TRL): NASA scale 1-9 measuring technology maturity (1=concept, 9=flight-proven)
```

**Acronyms:**

```
AGI: Artificial General Intelligence
CCS: Carbon Capture and Storage
CEA: Controlled Environment Agriculture
CLLS: Closed-Loop Life Support
COPUOS: Committee on the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space (UN)
ECLSS: Environmental Control and Life Support System
ESA: European Space Agency
EVA: Extravehicular Activity (spacewalk)
FAA: Federal Aviation Administration (US)
FCC: Federal Communications Commission (US)
FRAND: Fair, Reasonable, And Non-Discriminatory (licensing terms)
GEO: Geostationary Earth Orbit
ICNIRP: International Commission on Non-Ionizing Radiation Protection
IEEE: Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers
IP: Intellectual Property
IRR: Internal Rate of Return
ISM: Industrial, Scientific, and Medical (radio bands)
ISRA: International Space Resource Authority (proposed)
ISRU: In-Situ Resource Utilization
ISS: International Space Station
ITU: International Telecommunication Union
JAXA: Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency
kWh: Kilowatt-hour (energy unit)
L1, L2, L3, L4, L5: Lagrange Points
LCOE: Levelized Cost of Energy
LEO: Low Earth Orbit
LH2: Liquid Hydrogen
LOX: Liquid Oxygen (also LO2)
MAV: Mars Ascent Vehicle
MOXIE: Mars Oxygen In-Situ Resource Utilization Experiment
MW: Megawatt (power unit)
MWh: Megawatt-hour (energy unit)
NASA: National Aeronautics and Space Administration (US)
NEA: Near-Earth Asteroid
NPV: Net Present Value
NRHO: Near Rectilinear Halo Orbit
OpEx: Operational Expenditure
PCA: Permanent Court of Arbitration
PEM: Proton Exchange Membrane (fuel cell/electrolyzer technology)
PGM: Platinum Group Metals
PPFD: Photosynthetic Photon Flux Density (light intensity for plants)
ppm: Parts per million
PSR: Permanently Shadowed Region
PV: Photovoltaic (solar panels)
R&D: Research and Development
RF: Radio Frequency
ROI: Return on Investment
SAT: Space Arbitration Tribunal (proposed)
SBSP: Space-Based Solar Power
SCWO: Supercritical Water Oxidation
SDG: Sustainable Development Goals (UN)
SMR: Small Modular Reactor (nuclear)
SOEC: Solid Oxide Electrolyzer Cell
SRM: Solar Radiation Management
STEM: Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics
SWF: Sovereign Wealth Fund
TRL: Technology Readiness Level
TWh: Terawatt-hour (billion kilowatt-hours)
UN: United Nations
UNOOSA: United Nations Office for Outer Space Affairs
UPA: Urine Processor Assembly (ISS system)
USD: United States Dollar
VFA: Volatile Fatty Acid
WACC: Weighted Average Cost of Capital
WPA: Water Processor Assembly (ISS system)
WPT: Wireless Power Transmission
```

